1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 Hvala što pratite kanal.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:59,980
 Hvala što pratite kanal.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 Hvala što pratite kanal.

4
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,880
 as it was used by the fathers of the Council 1700 years ago

5
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:11,360
 to articulate the divine consubstantiality of the Son with the Father.

6
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:15,100
 During my presentation, I won't be reading the sources,

7
00:01:15,100 --> 00:01:18,620
 but they will be displayed on the PowerPoints on the slides

8
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:21,940
 and can be easily referenced throughout the presentation.

9
00:01:21,940 --> 00:01:29,040
 So, just to begin, approximately 75 years after the Council of Nicaea,

10
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,980
 at the outset of composing De Trinitate,

11
00:01:31,980 --> 00:01:35,780
 St. Augustine engaged in a public debate with Passentius,

12
00:01:35,780 --> 00:01:40,480
 an Aryan member of the imperial court, concerning the term homoousius.

13
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:45,700
 During the debate, Passentius advanced a well-known argument against the term,

14
00:01:45,700 --> 00:01:49,580
 asserting that homoousius does not appear in scripture.

15
00:01:49,580 --> 00:01:54,680
 In response, Augustine offered a nuanced and strategic rebuttal.

16
00:01:54,680 --> 00:01:58,340
 He first observed that, as a Greek term,

17
00:01:58,340 --> 00:02:02,600
 homoousius would not be expected to appear in the Latin scripture.

18
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:07,180
 However, rather than focusing solely on the presence of the term,

19
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:12,840
 Augustine emphasized the importance of identifying its scriptural meaning.

20
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:15,560
 Regarding its semantic equivalents,

21
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:18,720
 Augustine refrained from a straightforward translation,

22
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:24,280
 noting that alternatives such as eiusdem substantia or una substantia

23
00:02:24,280 --> 00:02:26,680
 might similarly be criticized

24
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:31,360
 for lacking direst scriptural attestation within the creed.

25
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:35,340
 Nonetheless, he argued that the concept itself,

26
00:02:35,340 --> 00:02:36,460
 res ipsa,

27
00:02:36,460 --> 00:02:38,620
 is indeed found in scripture.

28
00:02:38,620 --> 00:02:41,540
 Specifically, Augustine identified

29
00:02:41,540 --> 00:02:43,600
 Ego et pater unum sumus,

30
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:46,700
 as the Latin scriptural equivalent of homoousius.

31
00:02:46,700 --> 00:02:48,820
 Through this interpretation,

32
00:02:48,820 --> 00:02:51,980
 he asserted that the passage conveys the doctrinal truth

33
00:02:51,980 --> 00:02:56,220
 that the father and the son share the same nature and substance.

34
00:02:56,220 --> 00:03:00,560
 The aim of this paper is to examine the Trinitarian issues

35
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:02,080
 addressed by the First Council

36
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:06,520
 from the perspective of emerging Latin Christian literature.

37
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:10,940
 The question of alleged Western influences

38
00:03:10,940 --> 00:03:13,320
 on the historical and theological proceedings

39
00:03:13,320 --> 00:03:15,180
 of the First Council of Nicaea

40
00:03:15,180 --> 00:03:18,520
 has been a long-standing topic of scholarly debate.

41
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:19,940
 Early on,

42
00:03:19,940 --> 00:03:22,580
 the idea that Western theology influenced

43
00:03:22,580 --> 00:03:25,220
 or even originated the Nicene Creed

44
00:03:25,220 --> 00:03:27,400
 gained considerable support.

45
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:30,260
 Scholars such as Adolf von Harnack,

46
00:03:30,260 --> 00:03:32,140
 Taudor Zahn and Gustav Krüger

47
00:03:32,140 --> 00:03:34,640
 attempted to establish a connection

48
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:36,480
 between the strong emphasis

49
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:37,640
 on divine unity

50
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:39,840
 in the works of early Western theologians

51
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:41,280
 like Tertullian

52
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:44,000
 and the content of the Nicene Creed.

53
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,840
 However, over the past 50 years,

54
00:03:46,840 --> 00:03:49,540
 this theory has been seriously challenged

55
00:03:49,540 --> 00:03:52,260
 and subjected to significant criticism,

56
00:03:52,260 --> 00:03:55,340
 particularly with the work of Christopher Steed,

57
00:03:55,340 --> 00:03:57,500
 his work Divine Substance.

58
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,900
 I would argue that the proceedings

59
00:03:59,900 --> 00:04:01,860
 of the Council of Nicaea involved

60
00:04:01,860 --> 00:04:04,280
 considerable input from Western theology

61
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:06,420
 and that, at the very least,

62
00:04:06,420 --> 00:04:09,180
 Western influence cannot be dismissed.

63
00:04:09,180 --> 00:04:13,400
 To assess the extent of this Latin influence,

64
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:16,520
 it is crucial to first examine

65
00:04:16,520 --> 00:04:18,280
 the role of Hosseus of Cordoba

66
00:04:18,280 --> 00:04:20,060
 in the Council's proceedings,

67
00:04:20,060 --> 00:04:23,280
 as well as the origins of the term Homo usios,

68
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:26,480
 specifically whether Latin theological thought

69
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:28,680
 played a formative role in its adoption.

70
00:04:29,220 --> 00:04:31,140
 Additionally, a broader examination

71
00:04:31,140 --> 00:04:33,160
 of the Latin theological tradition

72
00:04:33,160 --> 00:04:36,200
 from Tertullian to Hilary is necessary.

73
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:38,220
 By analysing this tradition

74
00:04:38,220 --> 00:04:40,260
 in the context of the Nicene Council,

75
00:04:40,260 --> 00:04:42,860
 albeit in a preliminary manner,

76
00:04:42,860 --> 00:04:45,140
 we may gain a deeper understanding

77
00:04:45,140 --> 00:04:47,420
 of its potential contributions

78
00:04:47,420 --> 00:04:50,140
 to the development of the Trinitarian doctrine.

79
00:04:50,140 --> 00:04:52,760
 So it is crucial to begin

80
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:55,280
 by examining the role of Hosseus of Cordoba,

81
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:56,980
 who served as the president

82
00:04:56,980 --> 00:04:58,860
 of the Council of Nicaea

83
00:04:58,860 --> 00:05:01,520
 and an advisor to Emperor Constantine.

84
00:05:01,520 --> 00:05:05,060
 In 324, he was sent by the emperor

85
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:07,700
 to Alexandria to mediate the conflict

86
00:05:07,700 --> 00:05:09,820
 between Alexander and Arius.

87
00:05:09,820 --> 00:05:13,160
 He later presided over the Synod of Antioch

88
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:16,120
 in 325, as well as the councils

89
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:19,980
 of Cernica 342 and Sirmium 358.

90
00:05:19,980 --> 00:05:22,680
 In recent years, however,

91
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:25,920
 new perspectives have emerged,

92
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:27,700
 particularly through the work

93
00:05:27,700 --> 00:05:29,320
 of Brian Herbert Warmington.

94
00:05:29,320 --> 00:05:31,820
 Warmington has challenged the notion

95
00:05:31,820 --> 00:05:33,700
 that ecclesiastical figures,

96
00:05:33,700 --> 00:05:35,160
 including Hosseus,

97
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:38,240
 could have held advisory positions

98
00:05:38,240 --> 00:05:40,000
 within the emperor's inner council.

99
00:05:40,960 --> 00:05:43,120
 Furthermore, based on the Eusebius sources,

100
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:46,160
 he argues that Hosseus' role in these events

101
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:48,060
 may not have been as decisive

102
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:49,960
 as traditionally assumed.

103
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:51,560
 At the same time,

104
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:53,160
 Samuel Fernandes presents

105
00:05:53,160 --> 00:05:54,500
 a compelling argument

106
00:05:54,500 --> 00:05:56,800
 that Hosseus was the one

107
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:58,260
 who initiated the idea

108
00:05:58,260 --> 00:05:59,620
 of convening the council

109
00:05:59,620 --> 00:06:01,200
 and can be seen

110
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:02,860
 as its intellectual leader.

111
00:06:02,860 --> 00:06:05,480
 Evidence for this can be found

112
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:07,440
 in the letter of the Synod of Antioch,

113
00:06:07,780 --> 00:06:09,520
 written before Hosseus' supposed

114
00:06:09,520 --> 00:06:11,140
 peace mission had concluded,

115
00:06:11,140 --> 00:06:13,400
 that is, before his return

116
00:06:13,400 --> 00:06:14,300
 to Nicomedia.

117
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:16,900
 This letter mentions plans

118
00:06:16,900 --> 00:06:18,680
 for a great and priestly synod

119
00:06:18,680 --> 00:06:19,640
 in Ankura,

120
00:06:19,640 --> 00:06:21,980
 which was intended to offer

121
00:06:21,980 --> 00:06:23,360
 a place for repentance

122
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:24,680
 for the condemned bishops,

123
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:26,400
 including Eusebius.

124
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:28,780
 It seems that Hosseus had

125
00:06:28,780 --> 00:06:30,480
 the authority and autonomy

126
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:33,200
 to independently convene the council

127
00:06:33,200 --> 00:06:36,080
 based on his synodal experience,

128
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:38,120
 addressing the doctrinal divisions

129
00:06:38,120 --> 00:06:39,940
 threatening the unity of the Church.

130
00:06:39,940 --> 00:06:41,920
 While Sosamon states

131
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:43,860
 that Constantine convened the synod

132
00:06:43,860 --> 00:06:45,400
 following Hosseus' return,

133
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:47,080
 Rufinus suggests

134
00:06:47,080 --> 00:06:49,420
 that the decision was made

135
00:06:49,420 --> 00:06:51,120
 on the advice of the bishops.

136
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:52,620
 Notably,

137
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:54,500
 Sopisius Severus confirms

138
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:55,860
 Hosseus' central role,

139
00:06:55,860 --> 00:06:58,040
 stating that the Nicene council

140
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:00,600
 was convened under his authority.

141
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:03,540
 The discrepancies among sources

142
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:05,520
 can likely be attributed

143
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:06,480
 to Eusebius,

144
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:08,020
 whose account became

145
00:07:08,020 --> 00:07:09,920
 the dominant historical narrative.

146
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:12,780
 Eusebius deliberately omits

147
00:07:12,780 --> 00:07:14,400
 reference to Hosseus' mission

148
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:16,140
 and the synod of Antioch,

149
00:07:16,140 --> 00:07:19,400
 likely due to his excommunication there.

150
00:07:19,400 --> 00:07:21,400
 And he also ignores the plan

151
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:23,420
 for a priestly synod of Ankura,

152
00:07:23,420 --> 00:07:25,980
 instead presenting the council of Nicaea

153
00:07:25,980 --> 00:07:27,920
 as solely Constantine's initiative.

154
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:29,640
 Collectively,

155
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:30,460
 these factors,

156
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:31,440
 in my view,

157
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:33,620
 strongly support the conclusion

158
00:07:33,620 --> 00:07:35,760
 that Hosseus was the driving force

159
00:07:35,760 --> 00:07:37,360
 behind the convocation

160
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:38,520
 of what would become

161
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:40,300
 the first council of Nicaea.

162
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:42,700
 As the letter of the Antiochian synod

163
00:07:42,700 --> 00:07:43,480
 reinforces,

164
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:45,160
 he had the authority

165
00:07:45,160 --> 00:07:45,980
 and autonomy

166
00:07:45,980 --> 00:07:47,880
 to convene and preside

167
00:07:47,880 --> 00:07:49,180
 over such a council.

168
00:07:49,180 --> 00:07:52,080
 As previously mentioned,

169
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:53,140
 Homo Hosseus

170
00:07:53,140 --> 00:07:55,340
 is one of the most significant terms

171
00:07:55,340 --> 00:07:57,460
 introduced at the Council of Nicaea,

172
00:07:58,040 --> 00:07:59,780
 expressing the substantial unity

173
00:07:59,780 --> 00:08:01,320
 of the Son with the Father

174
00:08:01,320 --> 00:08:03,320
 in a Trinitarian context.

175
00:08:03,320 --> 00:08:05,840
 Our understanding of its use

176
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:07,020
 in the Nicene Creed

177
00:08:07,020 --> 00:08:08,360
 is primarily informed

178
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:10,080
 by three key sources,

179
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:12,900
 the accounts of Eusebius of Caesarea,

180
00:08:12,900 --> 00:08:14,120
 Athanasius,

181
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:15,400
 and Saint Ambrose.

182
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:17,100
 In the Fide,

183
00:08:17,100 --> 00:08:18,240
 Ambrose of Milan

184
00:08:18,240 --> 00:08:20,020
 attributes the origin of the term

185
00:08:20,020 --> 00:08:21,720
 to Eusebius of Nicomedia,

186
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:23,980
 who in a letter read

187
00:08:23,980 --> 00:08:24,740
 that the council

188
00:08:24,740 --> 00:08:27,160
 explicitly rejected Homo Hosseus

189
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:29,080
 condemning it

190
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:30,280
 as unacceptable

191
00:08:30,280 --> 00:08:31,720
 due to its perceived

192
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:33,360
 Saberlian connotations.

193
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:35,480
 According to Ambrose,

194
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:36,680
 the Nicene fathers

195
00:08:36,680 --> 00:08:38,360
 adopted the term largely

196
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:39,960
 for polemical reasons,

197
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:41,820
 using it to counter

198
00:08:41,820 --> 00:08:43,500
 the Arian theologians

199
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:44,960
 who had explicitly

200
00:08:44,960 --> 00:08:46,860
 rejected Homo Hosseus.

201
00:08:46,860 --> 00:08:48,700
 On the other hand,

202
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:50,180
 Athanasius credits

203
00:08:50,180 --> 00:08:51,300
 Hosseus of Cordoba

204
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:52,800
 with drafting the creed

205
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:54,060
 that was ultimately

206
00:08:54,060 --> 00:08:55,640
 adopted by Nicaea,

207
00:08:55,640 --> 00:08:57,040
 suggesting that

208
00:08:57,040 --> 00:08:58,760
 as president of the council

209
00:08:58,760 --> 00:09:00,260
 he was responsible

210
00:09:00,260 --> 00:09:02,000
 for introducing the term.

211
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:03,900
 This claim appears

212
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:05,060
 to be corroborated

213
00:09:05,060 --> 00:09:06,420
 by the Arian historian

214
00:09:06,420 --> 00:09:07,500
 Philostorgius,

215
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:08,800
 who reports that

216
00:09:08,800 --> 00:09:10,140
 Hosseus and Alexander

217
00:09:10,140 --> 00:09:11,360
 of Alexandria

218
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:13,480
 agreed on this concept

219
00:09:13,480 --> 00:09:15,120
 and jointly proposed

220
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:16,080
 it to the council.

221
00:09:17,280 --> 00:09:18,000
 Nevertheless,

222
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,160
 while political factors

223
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:21,400
 may have influenced

224
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:22,000
 Hosseus,

225
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:23,600
 particularly his role

226
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:24,520
 as a mediator

227
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:25,840
 between conflicting

228
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:26,520
 factions,

229
00:09:26,520 --> 00:09:28,400
 theological motivations

230
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:29,560
 should not be

231
00:09:29,560 --> 00:09:30,260
 overlooked.

232
00:09:30,940 --> 00:09:32,620
 The conceptual difficulties

233
00:09:32,620 --> 00:09:34,460
 surrounding Homo Hosseus,

234
00:09:34,460 --> 00:09:36,220
 such as its evolving

235
00:09:36,220 --> 00:09:37,060
 interpretation,

236
00:09:37,060 --> 00:09:38,220
 evidenced by

237
00:09:38,220 --> 00:09:39,600
 Marsalus of Anchura's

238
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:40,540
 use of Mia

239
00:09:40,540 --> 00:09:41,320
 hypostasis

240
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:42,720
 at the council of Serdica,

241
00:09:42,720 --> 00:09:44,520
 cannot simply be

242
00:09:44,520 --> 00:09:45,680
 attributed to a lack

243
00:09:45,680 --> 00:09:47,040
 of conceptual clarity

244
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:48,680
 on Hosseus' part.

245
00:09:48,680 --> 00:09:49,820
 Rather,

246
00:09:49,820 --> 00:09:51,720
 these terminological

247
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:53,420
 ambiguities reflect

248
00:09:53,420 --> 00:09:54,440
 broader theological

249
00:09:54,440 --> 00:09:55,240
 developments,

250
00:09:55,240 --> 00:09:56,440
 as the precise

251
00:09:56,440 --> 00:09:57,600
 distinction between

252
00:09:57,600 --> 00:09:58,580
 Hossea and

253
00:09:58,580 --> 00:09:59,380
 Hypostasis

254
00:09:59,380 --> 00:10:01,040
 was not fully resolved

255
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:01,880
 until the time

256
00:10:01,880 --> 00:10:02,940
 of the Cappadocian

257
00:10:02,940 --> 00:10:03,300
 fathers,

258
00:10:03,300 --> 00:10:04,440
 with the first

259
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:06,580
 council still

260
00:10:06,580 --> 00:10:07,240
 used them

261
00:10:07,240 --> 00:10:08,120
 synonymously.

262
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:10,240
 As noted by scholars

263
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:11,280
 like Theodor Zahn,

264
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:12,100
 Adolf von Harnach

265
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:13,200
 and Gustav Krüger,

266
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:14,340
 Homo Hosseus

267
00:10:14,340 --> 00:10:15,400
 can be understood

268
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:16,560
 as representing

269
00:10:16,560 --> 00:10:17,720
 the Latin theological

270
00:10:17,720 --> 00:10:18,900
 tradition,

271
00:10:18,900 --> 00:10:20,320
 the strong emphasis

272
00:10:20,320 --> 00:10:21,720
 on divine unity

273
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:23,060
 through the influence

274
00:10:23,060 --> 00:10:23,860
 of Hosseus.

275
00:10:23,860 --> 00:10:25,460
 In particular,

276
00:10:25,460 --> 00:10:26,620
 Tertullian's thought

277
00:10:26,620 --> 00:10:27,360
 appears to have

278
00:10:27,360 --> 00:10:28,660
 played a formative role

279
00:10:28,660 --> 00:10:30,380
 in Adversus Praxam,

280
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:31,560
 Tertullian was the

281
00:10:31,560 --> 00:10:32,480
 first to employ

282
00:10:32,480 --> 00:10:32,940
 the term

283
00:10:32,940 --> 00:10:34,240
 Una Substantia

284
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:35,640
 in a Trinitarian

285
00:10:35,640 --> 00:10:36,380
 context,

286
00:10:36,380 --> 00:10:37,560
 affirming that

287
00:10:37,560 --> 00:10:38,320
 the father and

288
00:10:38,320 --> 00:10:38,780
 the son

289
00:10:38,780 --> 00:10:39,880
 share the same

290
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:40,580
 substance.

291
00:10:40,580 --> 00:10:41,980
 This formulation

292
00:10:41,980 --> 00:10:42,960
 later became

293
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:43,980
